                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry>kilograms (kg)</entry>
                                <entry>metric tons (t)</entry>
                                <entry>0.001</entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry>metric tons (t)</entry>
                                <entry>kilograms (kg)</entry>
                                <entry>1000</entry>
                            </row>
                        </tbody>
                    </tgroup>
                </table>
                <para>
                    <emphasis emphasisType="em01">Precision:</emphasis> Round to 1 decimal place 
                    for masses under 100 kg, 0 decimal places for masses over 100 kg.
                </para>
            </levelledPara>
            
            <levelledPara>
                <title>Temperature Conversions</title>
                <para>
                    Temperature conversions are critical for cryogenic hydrogen systems. Use the 
                    following formulas:
                </para>
                <table>
                    <tgroup cols="2">
                        <thead>
                            <row>
                                <entry>Conversion</entry>
                                <entry>Formula</entry>
                            </row>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <row>
                                <entry>Celsius to Kelvin</entry>
                                <entry>K = °C + 273.15</entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry>Kelvin to Celsius</entry>
                                <entry>°C = K - 273.15</entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry>Celsius to Fahrenheit</entry>
                                <entry>°F = (°C × 9/5) + 32</entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry>Fahrenheit to Celsius</entry>
                                <entry>°C = (°F - 32) × 5/9</entry>
                            </row>
                        </tbody>
                    </tgroup>
                </table>
                <para>
                    <emphasis emphasisType="em01">Q100 Cryogenic Reference Points:</emphasis>
                </para>
                <table>
                    <tgroup cols="4">
                        <thead>
                            <row>
                                <entry>Reference</entry>
                                <entry>Kelvin</entry>
                                <entry>Celsius</entry>
                                <entry>Fahrenheit</entry>
                            </row>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <row>
                                <entry>LH₂ Boiling Point (1 atm)</entry>
                                <entry>20.28 K</entry>
                                <entry>-252.87°C</entry>
                                <entry>-423.17°F</entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry>LH₂ Operating Temperature</entry>
                                <entry>~20 K</entry>
                                <entry>~-253°C</entry>
                                <entry>~-423°F</entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry>Ambient (Standard Day)</entry>
                                <entry>288.15 K</entry>
                                <entry>15°C</entry>
                                <entry>59°F</entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry>Fuel Cell Operating Temp</entry>
                                <entry>333-353 K</entry>
                                <entry>60-80°C</entry>
                                <entry>140-176°F</entry>
                            </row>
                        </tbody>
                    </tgroup>
                </table>
                <para>
                    <emphasis emphasisType="em01">Precision:</emphasis> Use 2 decimal places for 
                    cryogenic temperatures, 1 decimal place for ambient temperatures, 0 decimal 
                    places for high temperatures (>100°C).
                </para>
            </levelledPara>
            
