            <levelledPara>
                <title>H₂-Specific Units and Conversions</title>
                <para>
                    The following specialized units are used for hydrogen systems on the Q100:
                </para>
                
                <levelledPara>
                    <title>Energy Density</title>
                    <table>
                        <tgroup cols="3">
                            <thead>
                                <row>
                                    <entry>Quantity</entry>
                                    <entry>Value (Mass Basis)</entry>
                                    <entry>Value (Volume Basis)</entry>
                                </row>
                            </thead>
                            <tbody>
                                <row>
                                    <entry>LH₂ Energy Density</entry>
                                    <entry>120 MJ/kg (33.3 kWh/kg)</entry>
                                    <entry>8.5 MJ/L (2.36 kWh/L)</entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry>GH₂ Energy Density (700 bar)</entry>
                                    <entry>120 MJ/kg (33.3 kWh/kg)</entry>
                                    <entry>5.6 MJ/L (1.56 kWh/L)</entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry>Jet-A Energy Density (Reference)</entry>
                                    <entry>43 MJ/kg (11.9 kWh/kg)</entry>
                                    <entry>34 MJ/L (9.4 kWh/L)</entry>
                                </row>
                            </tbody>
                        </tgroup>
                    </table>
                </levelledPara>
                
                <levelledPara>
                    <title>Boil-Off Rate</title>
                    <para>
                        Boil-off rate is expressed as percentage of total tank capacity lost per 
                        day (%/day):
                    </para>
                    <para>
                        <verbatimText verbatimStyle="vs11">
Boil-off Rate (%/day) = (Mass Loss per Day / Initial Mass) × 100

Example:
Initial LH₂ mass: 1000 kg
Mass loss after 24h: 3 kg
Boil-off rate = (3 / 1000) × 100 = 0.3%/day
                        </verbatimText>
                    </para>
                    <para>
                        <emphasis emphasisType="em01">Q100 Design Target:</emphasis> ≤ 0.5%/day 
                        with zero-boil-off (ZBO) cryocooler active.
                    </para>
                </levelledPara>
                
                <levelledPara>
                    <title>Flow Rates</title>
                    <table>
                        <tgroup cols="3">
                            <thead>
                                <row>
                                    <entry>From</entry>
                                    <entry>To</entry>
                                    <entry>Conversion</entry>
                                </row>
                            </thead>
                            <tbody>
                                <row>
                                    <entry>kg/s</entry>
                                    <entry>kg/h</entry>
                                    <entry>Multiply by 3600</entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry>kg/h</entry>
                                    <entry>kg/s</entry>
                                    <entry>Divide by 3600</entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry>L/min (LH₂)</entry>
                                    <entry>kg/h (LH₂)</entry>
                                    <entry>Multiply by 4.251 (at 20K)</entry>
                                </row>
                            </tbody>
                        </tgroup>
                    </table>
                    <para>
                        <emphasis emphasisType="em01">Q100 Fuel Cell Consumption:</emphasis> 
                        Maximum consumption rate at full power (2.5 MW per stack): ~0.047 kg/s 
                        or ~170 kg/h of hydrogen.
                    </para>
                </levelledPara>
            </levelledPara>
            
            <levelledPara>
                <title>Precision and Rounding Rules</title>
                <para>
                    Use the following rounding rules based on measurement type and magnitude:
                </para>
                <table>
                    <tgroup cols="3">
                        <thead>
                            <row>
                                <entry>Quantity Type</entry>
                                <entry>Magnitude Range</entry>
                                <entry>Rounding Rule</entry>
                            </row>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <row>
                                <entry>Length</entry>
                                <entry>&lt; 1 m</entry>
                                <entry>1 decimal place (mm precision)</entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry>Length</entry>
                                <entry>≥ 1 m</entry>
                                <entry>2 decimal places (cm precision)</entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry>Mass</entry>
                                <entry>&lt; 100 kg</entry>
                                <entry>1 decimal place</entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry>Mass</entry>
                                <entry>≥ 100 kg</entry>
                                <entry>0 decimal places (whole kg)</entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry>Temperature (Cryogenic)</entry>
                                <entry>&lt; 100 K</entry>
                                <entry>2 decimal places</entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry>Temperature (Ambient)</entry>
                                <entry>100-500 K</entry>
                                <entry>1 decimal place</entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry>Pressure</entry>
                                <entry>&lt; 10 bar</entry>
                                <entry>2 decimal places</entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry>Pressure</entry>
                                <entry>≥ 10 bar</entry>
                                <entry>0 decimal places (whole bar)</entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry>Energy Density</entry>
                                <entry>All ranges</entry>
                                <entry>1 decimal place</entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry>Flow Rate</entry>
                                <entry>All ranges</entry>
                                <entry>3 decimal places for kg/s, 1 for kg/h</entry>
                            </row>
                        </tbody>
                    </tgroup>
                </table>
                <para>
                    <emphasis emphasisType="em01">Significant Figures:</emphasis> Maintain 
                    appropriate significant figures through calculations. Final results should 
                    not exceed precision of least precise input.
                </para>
            </levelledPara>
            
            <levelledPara>
                <title>Example Calculations</title>
                <para>
                    The following examples demonstrate proper unit conversion and precision for 
                    typical Q100 operations:
                </para>
                
                <levelledPara>
                    <title>Example 1: Fuel Load Calculation</title>
                    <para>
                        <emphasis emphasisType="em01">Problem:</emphasis> Calculate LH₂ fuel load 
                        in pounds given 450 kg of hydrogen.
                    </para>
                    <para>
                        <verbatimText verbatimStyle="vs11">
Given: 450 kg LH₂
Conversion factor: 1 kg = 2.20462 lb

Calculation:
450 kg × 2.20462 lb/kg = 992.079 lb

Rounded per precision rule (≥100 lb → 0 decimal places):
Answer: 992 lb
                        </verbatimText>
                    </para>
                </levelledPara>
                
                <levelledPara>
                    <title>Example 2: Cryogenic Temperature Conversion</title>
                    <para>
                        <emphasis emphasisType="em01">Problem:</emphasis> Convert LH₂ tank 
                        temperature from 20.5 K to Celsius and Fahrenheit.
                    </para>
                    <para>
                        <verbatimText verbatimStyle="vs11">
Given: 20.5 K

To Celsius:
°C = K - 273.15
°C = 20.5 - 273.15 = -252.65°C

To Fahrenheit:
°F = (°C × 9/5) + 32
°F = (-252.65 × 1.8) + 32 = -422.77°F

Rounded per precision rule (cryogenic → 2 decimal places):
Answer: -252.65°C or -422.77°F
                        </verbatimText>
                    </para>
                </levelledPara>
                
                <levelledPara>
                    <title>Example 3: Energy Calculation</title>
                    <para>
                        <emphasis emphasisType="em01">Problem:</emphasis> Calculate total energy 
                        content of 450 kg LH₂ in MJ and kWh.
                    </para>
                    <para>
                        <verbatimText verbatimStyle="vs11">
Given: 450 kg LH₂
Energy density: 120 MJ/kg

Energy in MJ:
E = 450 kg × 120 MJ/kg = 54,000 MJ

Energy in kWh:
E = 54,000 MJ × 0.277778 kWh/MJ = 15,000 kWh

Answer: 54,000 MJ or 15,000 kWh
                        </verbatimText>
                    </para>
                </levelledPara>
            </levelledPara>
            
            <levelledPara>
                <title>Usage Notes</title>
                <para>
                    <emphasis emphasisType="em01">Mandatory Use:</emphasis> All technical 
